        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer494986950" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13960764098233175340">This book drew me in on the very first page when daring, adventurous socialite Marguerite Westing is being courted by the wealthy Roger Gordon (who her mother desperately wants her to marry). While on a date with him, she is afraid of dying of boredom and pens this epitaph in her head:<br/><br/>Here lies Marguerite Westing.<br/>Only nineteen, but now she&apos;s resting.<br/>Strolling through the park with Roger Gordon, <br/>Once full of life, she died of boredom.<br/><br/>She is saved from complete boredom when her dad announces they </span>
  <span id="freeText13960764098233175340" style="display:none">This book drew me in on the very first page when daring, adventurous socialite Marguerite Westing is being courted by the wealthy Roger Gordon (who her mother desperately wants her to marry). While on a date with him, she is afraid of dying of boredom and pens this epitaph in her head:<br /><br />Here lies Marguerite Westing.<br />Only nineteen, but now she's resting.<br />Strolling through the park with Roger Gordon, <br />Once full of life, she died of boredom.<br /><br />She is saved from complete boredom when her dad announces they are moving to the lake for the summer. At the lake, Marguerite sees sailing for the first time. Sailing really appeals to Marguerite's adventurous side and she knows she must learn how. A few obstacles: she can't swim, it's 1895 and inappropriate for young ladies to learn how to sail, her mother will never approve, and Roger will definitely not approve. <br /><br />But Marguerite is crafty and she convinces her younger brother that he wants to learn to sail and then convinces her father that she needs to oversee his lessons to make sure he doesn't get into trouble. <br /><br />At first Marguerite sees Trip Andrews, the sailing instructor, as arrogant and uncaring, but then she gets to know him better and begins to care for him. Trip embraces her adventurous side and loves her the way she is -- unlike her mother and Roger who are always trying to change her.<br /><br />But at the same time her feelings are getting stronger for Trip, her courtship with Roger is getting deeper and deeper and she doesn't know how to stop it. She realizes too late that she should have told Roger the truth at the very beginning of the courtship -- that she didn't have feelings for him. Roger has moved beyond boring and is now becoming dangerous.<br /><br />And then she finds out her father's dark secret that can destroy their family. Marrying Roger will solve her parents' problems and so instead of telling Roger the truth, she becomes engaged to him. Roger becomes more dangerous and possessive and Marguerite is driven to the point where she has to decide to be completely honest with everyone and trust that God will work everything out.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13960764098233175340" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


